  "prompt": "Why is mercury in a thermometer red?",
  "response": "Actually, mercury in a thermometer doesn't appear red; it's typically a silver or gray color because mercury is a shiny, silver liquid metal. The confusion might arise from alcohol-based thermometers, where the alcohol is dyed red or another color to make it easier to read. In contrast, mercury thermometers use the natural color of mercury and are contained within a thin glass tube. The clear glass combined with the reflective mercury gives it its characteristic appearance. \n\nHowever, due to safety concerns regarding mercury's toxicity, many countries have moved towards using alcohol or digital thermometers as safer alternatives.",
